<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Drawing paper or canvases","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pencils, charcoal, drawing pens","isOptional":false},{"name":"Paints (acrylic or watercolor)","isOptional":false},{"name":"Rulers or straight edges","isOptional":false},{"name":"Images of buildings, cityscapes, and urban scenes (from photographs, magazines, newspapers, etc.)","isOptional":false},{"name":"Whiteboard or projector","isOptional":false},{"name":"Markers","isOptional":false},{"name":"Notebooks or paper","isOptional":false},{"name":"Pens/Pencils","isOptional":false}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Cubist Cities: Building a Vision of Sustainable Communities Through Art"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin by showing a slideshow/images of iconic Cubist paintings.<br>Examples\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_City_%28L%C3%A9ger%29#/media/File:Fernand_L%C3%A9ger,_1919,_The_City_</li>\n</ul><br>(La_Ville<br>\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The City</em></a>,_oil_on_canvas,_231.1_x_298.4_cm,_Philadelphia_Museum_of_Art.jpg)<em>,</em> Fernand Léger\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/fernand-leger/men-in-the-city-1919\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Men in the City</em></a><em>,</em> Fernand Léger</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/lyubov-popova/cubist-landscape-city-1914\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Cubist Landscape City</em></a><em>,</em> Lyubov Popova</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.artic.edu/artworks/111060/daniel-henry-kahnweiler\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Daniel-Henry Kahnweiler</em></a><em>,</em> Pablo Picasso</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/pablo-picasso/still-life-with-the-caned-chair-1912\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Still Life with Caned Chair</em></a><em>,</em> Pablo Picasso</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://modernarthistoryfall2012.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/demoiselles.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Les Demoiselles d’Avignon, Pablo Picasso</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.pablopicasso.org/guernica.jsp#google_vignette\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Guernica, Pablo Picasso</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.singulart.com/en/blog/2024/10/25/houses-at-lestaque-by-georges-braque-bc/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Houses at l’Estaque, Georges Braque</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.georgesbraque.org/violin-and-candlestick.jsp#google_vignette\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Violin and Candlestick, Georges Braque</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wikiart.org/en/juan-gris/portrait-of-pablo-picasso-1912\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Portrait of Pablo Picasso, Juan Gris</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.metmuseum.org/perspectives/juan-gris-still-life-with-checked-tablecloth\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Still Life with Checked Tablecloth, Juan Gris</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.moma.org/collection/works/79078\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The City and Three Women, Fernand Léger</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.arthistoryproject.com/artists/maria-blanchard/still-life-with-green-lamp/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Still Life with Green Lamp, María Blanchard</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.arthistoryproject.com/artists/maria-blanchard/woman-seated/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Woman Seated, María Blanchard</a></li>\n</ul><br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>What do you notice about these paintings?</li>\n<li>How do they make you feel?</li>\n<li>What do you think the artists were trying to express?</li>\n</ul><br>Facilitate a discussion about the key characteristics of Cubism<br>Key Points\n<ul>\n<li>An early 20th-century avant-garde art movement that revolutionized European painting and sculpture.</li>\n<li>Challenged traditional perspectives and representation, depicting subjects from multiple viewpoints simultaneously.</li>\n<li>Emphasized geometric forms, fragmentation, and the two-dimensionality of the canvas.</li>\n<li>Often incorporated collage elements and mixed media.</li>\n</ul><br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>How is Cubism different from traditional art styles?</li>\n<li>Why do you think the Cubists chose to fragment and distort their subjects?</li>\n<li>How does Cubism challenge our perception of reality?</li>\n</ul><br>Introduct/re-introduce Global Goal 11: Sustainable Cities and Communities. Explain the core idea of making citiesand human settlements inclusive, safe, resilient, and sustainable.<br>Briefly introduce the different targets within Global Goal 11, highlighting their interconnectedness and importance.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>What are some of the challenges facing cities today?</li>\n<li>How can we make cities more sustainable and livable for everyone?</li>\n<li>What role can art play in promoting sustainable development?</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exploring Cubist Techniques"} content={"<em>Fragmentation:</em> Discuss how Cubists fragmented objects and figures into geometric shapes and planes, showing them from multiple perspectives simultaneously.<br>In five minutes or less, have students quickly practice fragmenting simple objects (e.g., a cup, a chair, a building, etc.) into geometric shapes, drawing them from different angles and viewpoints.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>How does fragmentation change the way we see an object?</li>\n<li>How can fragmentation be used to represent the complexity of urban environments?</li>\n</ul><br><em>Geometric Forms:</em> Discuss how Cubists used geometric shapes (cubes, cones, cylinders, spheres, etc.) to construct their compositions.<br>In five minutes or less, have students quickly practice drawing and arranging geometric shapes to create abstract or semi-abstrict compositions.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>How do geometric forms contribute to the visual impact of Cubist art?</li>\n<li>How can geometric forms be used to represent different aspects of a city or community?</li>\n</ul><br><em>Multiple Viewpoints:</em> Discuss how Cubists challenged traditional perspective by showing objects and scenes from multiple viewpoints at once.<br>In five minutes or less, have students choose an object or scene and draw it from at least three different perspectives, combining these views into a single composition.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>How does seeing an object from multiple viewpoints change our understanding of it?</li>\n<li>How can multiple viewpoints be used to represent the diversity and complexity of urban life?</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Cubism and Global Goal 11"} content={"<p>Facilitate and brainstorming session where students generate ideas for Cubist-inspired artwork that connects to the different targets within Global Goal 11.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>What are some visual metaphors or symbols that could represent each target?</li>\n<li>How can we use Cubist techniques to convey the challenges and opportunities associated with each target?</li>\n<li>How can we use Cubism to inspire action and encourage people to contribute to achieving Global Goal 11?</li>\n</ul><br>Examples\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 11.1</strong> <em>(Affordable Housing):</em> Create a Cubist work of a diverse community with a variety of housing options, emphasizing inclusivity and accessibility.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Transportation):</em> Design a Cubist work depicting different modes of transportation, highlighting the interconnectedness of a city’s transportation network.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.3</strong> <em>(Inclusive Urbanization):</em> Create a Cubist work of a city with overlapping perspectives and diverse communities, representing the complexity and dynamism of urban life.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.4</strong> <em>(Cultural Heritage):</em> Develop a Cubist work incorporating images of historical landmarks and cultural artifacts, emphasizing the importance of preserving cultural heritage.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.5</strong> <em>(Disaster Resilience):</em> Create a Cubist work depicting a city before, during, and after a natural disaster, highlighting the importance of resilient infrastructure and disaster preparedness.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.6</strong> <em>(Environmental Impact):</em> Create a Cubist work with contrasting images of pollution and clean energy, representing the environmental challenges and opportunities facing cities.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.7</strong> <em>(Green Spaces):</em> Develop a Cubist painting of a city with integrated green spaces, parks, and gardens, emphasizing the importance of nature in urban environments.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.a</strong> <em>(Urban-Rural Links):</em> Create a Cubist work that combines images of urban and rural landscapes, emphasizing the interconnectedness of these environments and the importance of sustainable development that benefits both.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.b</strong> <em>(Disaster Risk Reduction):</em> Create a Cubist painting that depicts a city’s response to a natural disaster, using fragmented perspectives and dynamic compositions to convey the chaos and resilience of the community.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.c</strong> <em>(Sustainable Buildings in Least Developed Countries):</em> Create a Cubist work that depicts a sustainable building in a least developed county, using fragmented perspectives and geometric forms to showcase the integration of traditional building techniques with modern sustainable practices.</li>\n</ul><br>Each student selects one target from Global Goal 11 (or can focus on the Goal holistically) and creates a Cubist-inspired artwork that represents a specific aspect of that target/goal.<br>Encourage students to experiment with different Cubist techniques to convey their chosen message effectively.<br>While students work, circulate to observe, offer encouragement, and answer questions.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>How are you using fragmentation to represent this target?</li>\n<li>What message are you trying to convey with your use of geometric forms?</li>\n<li>How does your artwork encourage viewers to think about sustainable cities and communities?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exhibition and Discussion"} content={"<p>Once the artwork is complete, have students display their creations around the classroom. Allow time for students to walk around, view each other’s work, and engage in informal discussions.<br>Facilitate a class discussion about the artwork, focusing on the connection to Global Goal 11 and the effectiveness of the Cubist techniques.<br>Guiding Questions\n<ul>\n<li>What are some of the most powerful or impactful artworks you saw?</li>\n<li>How did the different artworks make you think differently about Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>What are some of the common themes or messages you noticed in the artwork?</li>\n<li>How did the use of Cubist techniques enhance the message of the artwork?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did exploring Cubism, with its focus on fragmentation and multiple perspectives, influence your approach to creating your artwork about sustainable cities?</li>\n<li>What artistic choices did you make in terms of color, shape, and composition to represent the complexities and challenges of urban environments?</li>\n<li>Did experimenting with Cubist techniques help you see the subject matter (sustainable cities) in a new or unexpected way?</li>\n<li>How did the process of creating a Cubist artwork allow you to express your ideas and feelings about Global Goal 11 beyond a purely representational style?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of abstract art to communicate complex social and environmental issues?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 11 and the importance of sustainable cities and communities through this artistic expression?</li>\n<li>How did the different artworks created by your classmates broaden your understanding of the various dimensions of Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>Did creating artwork focused on a specific idea surrounding Global Goal 11 help you connect with the challenges and opportunities on a deeper level?</li>\n<li>How did the use of Cubist techniques enhance of alter the message about sustainable cities compared to a more traditional artistic approach?</li>\n<li>Did creating your artwork spark any personal connections or reflections on your own experiences with cities and sustainability in your community?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with while creating your artwork, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>What are some of the key takeaways from the artworks and discussions today that you think are important for others to understand about sustainable cities?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the introduction to Cubism, technique explorations, individual art creation, and class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 11, targets and core concepts. This will be evidenced through the symbolism and intention within the artwork and the verbal explanations during sharing and discussion.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in applying chosen Cubist elements (e.g., fragmentation, geometric forms, multiple viewpoints) to convey the message about sustainable cities. Look for innovative visual interpretations.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the finished artwork communicates its intended message about Global Goal 11. Did the artwork successfully evoke thought or emotion related to the goal?</li>\n<li>Willingness to experiment with the materials and techniques, embracing the unique qualities of Cubism, and problem-solving during the creative process.</li>\n<li>Ability to articulate artistic choices and to interpret and provide thoughtful feedback on classmates’ artwork, connecting it to Glboal Goal 11.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of art in social change and the complexities of achieving sustainable cities.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
